LGPL §6 — relinking
-------------------

LGPL-2.1 §6 requires that recipients of an LGPL'd library be able
to relink the application against a modified version of the
library. synthmodem satisfies this in the standard way for shared
libraries: glibc is loaded as a dynamic shared object (`.so`) by
the runtime VM, so a recipient may substitute a modified
`libc.so.6`, `libm.so.6`, or `ld-linux.so.2` at `vm/libc/` without
rebuilding any of the binaries that depend on it. No static
linking of glibc into a synthmodem-distributed binary occurs.

Corresponding source
--------------------

LGPL-2.1 §4 incorporates the GPL-2.0 source-distribution
obligations (see GPL-2.0 §3(a)). That obligation is satisfied by
committing the upstream Debian source set to this repository at:

  vm/sources/glibc_2.36.orig.tar.xz
  vm/sources/glibc_2.36-9+deb12u13.debian.tar.xz
  vm/sources/glibc_2.36-9+deb12u13.dsc

SHA256 sums for all three files are pinned in
`vm/sources/SHA256SUMS`. The top-level `COPYING` enumerates these
paths in its GPL corresponding-source statement.

Modifications from upstream
---------------------------

None. synthmodem redistributes the unmodified Debian binary
package contents. If synthmodem ever ships a patched glibc, this
notice must be updated to record the nature of the modifications,
per LGPL-2.1 §2.
